The roots are complex conjugates, so \( |z_1| = |z_2| = \sqrt{10} \). The points \( z_1 \), \( z_2 \), \( \frac{1}{z_1} \), and \( \frac{1}{z_2} \) form a convex quadrilateral \( \mathcal{Q} \). We parametrize the roots as \( z_1 = \sqrt{10} e^{i\theta} \) and \( z_2 = \sqrt{10} e^{-i\theta} \). Their reciprocals are \( \frac{1}{z_1} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{10}} e^{-i\theta} \) and \( \frac{1}{z_2} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{10}} e^{i\theta} \). Using the shoelace formula to calculate the area of the quadrilateral formed by these points, we find the area is given by: \[ \text{Area} = \frac{99}{10} |\cos\theta \sin\theta| \] The maximum value of \( |\cos\theta \sin\theta| \) is \( \frac{1}{2} \), which occurs when \( \theta = \frac{\pi}{4} \). At this angle, \( \cos\theta = \sin\theta = \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2} \). Substituting \( \theta = \frac{\pi}{4} \) into \( c = 2\sqrt{10} \cos\theta \), we get: \[ c = 2\sqrt{10} \cdot \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2} = \sqrt{20} \] Thus, \( c = \sqrt{m} \) implies \( m = 20 \). The value of \( m \) is \(\boxed{20}\).
